	(2982,18,'Ben','ben@hozzamedia.com','','86.160.128.234','2011-01-13 10:02:30','2011-01-13 15:02:30','Thank you',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2983,18,'Keilaron','keilaron@hotmail.com','http://keilaron.ca/','72.1.218.66','2011-01-19 14:42:58','2011-01-19 19:42:58','I think he was referring to pixels having (at least) two different ways they can vary: resolution and DPI. For example, my mother (who\'s eyesight is slowly degrading) has her resolution set to 1024x768 even though her monitor is capable of much more: This is to make things more legible.\nUnfortunately, on mobile devices and such these are usually locked to static setting.',0,'1','','',2905,0),
	(2984,18,'thatmtnman','thatmtnman@hotmail.com','','68.145.219.67','2011-01-22 20:39:21','2011-01-23 01:39:21','this was brilliant, and so very very useful. Not to mention clear. Thank you so much!!  I look forward to reading all of your work if it is this clear, concise, and well laid out.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2985,18,'Mike Edward Moras (e-sushi™)','e-sushi@gmx.net','http://www.e-sushi.net/','82.113.106.155','2011-01-25 10:51:15','2011-01-25 15:51:15','You got that one wrong... it\'s:\n\nbody{font-size:100.01%}\n\nand it forces Opera in using floats for calculation. Yet, that was for Opera7. I don\'t know if that\'s still applicable.\n\n\n\nThe \n\nbody{font:62.5% sans-serif}\n\nsimply does what allready has been said in previous comments... since browsers base 100% font size at 16px most of the time, this will recalculate it down to 52.5% which results in 10px.',0,'1','','',2937,0),
	(2986,18,'Christian','chross@gmx.de','','92.224.226.139','2011-02-03 05:50:52','2011-02-03 10:50:52','Thanks for the article.\nIt is good you included the addendum as that information was exactly what I was after.\nYou find many articles on the web on the use of em over px or any other dimension but most articles date back to around 2008 or something.\n\nThanks again for the update.\n\nCheers,\nChristian',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2987,18,'DC','developerchris@rebel.com.au','','203.26.122.12','2011-02-03 20:13:04','2011-02-04 01:13:04','In your addendum you say you are sticking to 62.5% body in other words almost 40% smaller than the \'desired size\' as set by the user. By not changing the default size in the browser a user is effectively saying that is their desired size.\n\nWhy would you want to override the users preferences?',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2988,18,'DC','developerchris@rebel.com.au','','203.26.122.12','2011-02-03 20:27:39','2011-02-04 01:27:39','Further to my last comment I just played with your css to see how it looked in my browser with your 62.5% disabled it was HUGE, that\'s when I found you also have a wrapper that uses a font size of 1.5em effectively negating the 62.5%.\n\nIs there a reason you do this?',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2989,18,'Kyle','kylersc@gmail.com','https://kyleschaeffer.com','68.229.126.69','2011-02-03 22:18:35','2011-02-04 03:18:35','Setting the body to 62.5% places the text at the equivalent of 10 pixels (which is very small, as you say).  This makes it much easier to use ems, however, because you can use 1.5em to create a font size that is exactly 15 pixels in most browsers.  2em is 20 pixels, 1.8em is 18 pixels, so on and so forth.  This is just a convenient way to quickly match a site\'s design to what you might see in a Photoshop file.',0,'1','','',2988,1),
	(2990,18,'Mikael','loveisliving@gmail.com','','213.64.81.145','2011-02-06 15:02:22','2011-02-06 20:02:22','Thanks for the article! I just read the book bulletproof web design, and wanted to make sure nothing had changed since 2007. The use of 62.5%, is the most consistent solution I have seen so far, it makes it far easier to know what size the EM matches in PX.',0,'1','','',2989,0),
	(2991,18,'Frederick Tshimanga','tshimanga@gmail.com','','41.177.72.244','2011-02-08 02:39:11','2011-02-08 07:39:11','great article',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2992,18,'Setting Type on the Web &#8211; Tips | Big Name','','http://heybigname.com/2011/02/08/setting-type-on-the-web-tips/','70.32.85.198','2011-02-08 21:52:58','2011-02-09 02:52:58','[...] CSS Font-Size: em vs. px vs. pt vs. percent | Kyle Schaeffer &#8211; Web Design and SharePoint Brand... &#8211; A nice font size overview with a 2011 update towards the end. [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),
	(2993,18,'TK','no@email.com','','66.41.101.233','2011-02-11 23:46:20','2011-02-12 04:46:20','While using em vs. px, both have its advantages and disadvantages. Using em in body copy is good, but using it in your menu text is bad. I have had countless times where I\'ve had to fix a site somebody designed using em\'s in menu text and when the user magnifies their browser page, the menu breaks off the page because the text size grows but can\'t handle the structure it\'s sitting in. Not sure if it\'s bad form regarding standards, but using em is best in body copy only.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2994,18,'David Kullmann','kullmann.david@gmail.com','','69.86.33.74','2011-02-14 16:01:49','2011-02-14 21:01:49','You are a pwner, good job.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2995,18,'Hutcho','hutch120@gmail.com','http://www.clearlysecure.com.au','203.214.36.55','2011-02-15 00:33:58','2011-02-15 05:33:58','Most modern browsers now support font-size tags such as small, large and so on with quite a decent range of sizes from xx-small to xx-large. Obviously if you want pixel perfect fonts then this is not for you, but these are not relative to the parent and so provide an easy way to avoid the em,px,pt,% issues and IMO address most font size needs.\n\nhttp://www.w3schools.com/css/pr_font_font-size.asp',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2996,18,'Shanna','studio@customlogozone.com','http://customlogozone.com','75.213.40.62','2011-03-01 04:34:18','2011-03-01 09:34:18','Great Article...Very Helpful. Thank You!!',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(2997,18,'Heath','heath@object9.com','','70.164.50.72','2011-03-01 12:04:49','2011-03-01 17:04:49','This is closer to the method I use. Any enclosed navigation or text I lock down with px. The rest of the copy is em based off of the 62.5 % body tag. Keeps menus and things that can\'t scale without breaking nice and neat.',0,'1','','',2993,0),
	(2998,18,'Pixels and EMs in web development','','http://degisn.com/?p=382','65.254.224.23','2011-03-08 15:58:42','2011-03-08 20:58:42','[...] order to take advantage of these capabilities, a developer needs to understand some key concepts. Kyle Schaeffer and Jon Tan provide some great explanations of the use of em&#8217;s over the use of pixels for [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),
	(2999,18,'[SVG/CSS] ex/em berechnen - Delphi-PRAXiS','','http://www.delphipraxis.net/158977-%5Bsvg-css%5D-ex-em-berechnen.html#post1087189','88.198.53.15','2011-03-10 02:17:20','2011-03-10 07:17:20','[...] [SVG/CSS] ex/em berechnen &nbsp;  Heute, 08:17    https://kyleschaeffer.com/best-practi...s-px-vs-pt-vs/     Thomas WassermannDas Problem steckt meistens zwischen den Ohren  [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),
	(3000,18,'Alex Miller','amiller@trileafdesigns.com','','70.239.212.215','2011-03-11 16:25:59','2011-03-11 21:25:59','I always use pixels and haven\'t really run into any problems or complaints. Keeping everything positioned right using precentages or ems is a rough business.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3001,18,'J.D.&#039;s Developer Widgets &raquo; More interesting Interview Questions','','http://develwidgets.com/?p=104','97.74.144.122','2011-03-15 01:01:51','2011-03-15 06:01:51','[...] In theory, the em unit is the new and upcoming standard for font sizes on the web, but in practice, the percent unit seems to provide a more consistent and accessible display for users. When client settings have changed, percent text scales at a reasonable rate, allowing designers to preserve readability, accessibility, and visual design. (For more https://kyleschaeffer.com/best-practices/css-font-size-em-vs-px-vs-pt-vs/) [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),
	(3002,18,'J.D.&#039;s Developer Widgets &raquo; More interesting Interview Questions','','http://develwidgets.com/?p=104','97.74.144.122','2011-03-15 01:01:52','2011-03-15 06:01:52','[...] In theory, the em unit is the new and upcoming standard for font sizes on the web, but in practice, the percent unit seems to provide a more consistent and accessible display for users. When client settings have changed, percent text scales at a reasonable rate, allowing designers to preserve readability, accessibility, and visual design. (For more https://kyleschaeffer.com/best-practices/css-font-size-em-vs-px-vs-pt-vs/) [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),
	(3003,18,'Web Developer','matt@supint.com','http://www.supint.com','24.17.48.125','2011-03-16 16:20:24','2011-03-16 21:20:24','I used to use px exclusively, too, until I saw that the font size got screwy on iPhones.  Have been using em since then and it\'s a lot more consistent, although I still struggle with nested font sizes.',0,'1','','',3000,0),
	(3004,18,'narvolicious','greg@leftylimbo.com','http://www.leftylimbo.com','99.98.1.173','2011-04-06 18:38:41','2011-04-06 23:38:41','Thanks for the great article and info. It really clears up a lot of things. Taking your advice along with the px use for navigation elements (and other stuff I don\'t want to break) seems to be the best way to go. I\'ll definitely apply it to the next site I build.',0,'1','','',0,0),
