	(3157,18,'Sharath','sharathcumar@gmail.com','','122.166.208.201','2015-05-27 07:35:11','2015-05-27 11:35:11','I happened to built a Responsive website recently, and am using media query to change the font size, for desktop and laptop browser version. The IE11 does \'not\' change the font size on laptop browser when used in \'px\',  So the solution is to use \'em\' instead of \'px\'? I mean why would not IE11 resize the font size?',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3158,18,'HJ','muafat@hotmail.com','','92.108.104.148','2015-06-23 08:44:20','2015-06-23 12:44:20','After trying different methods I can only say that I\'m using the good ol\' px units for my websites.\n\nThen there\'s that: \"Oh no, you shouldn\'t do that, because you\'re making people upset who have their browser font size set to something else.\" Allright, that might be a very small percentage of users. If they can\'t read it, use the zoom function. I\'m sorry, I can\'t please all of you guys.\n\nThen there\'s the: \"Oh no, you shouldn\'t do that, companies have spent millions of dollars to decide what font size looks best on a mobile device.\" Allright, amazing. But do you really think that I\'m going to set the body font size to 5px for smaller viewports?\n\nI\'ve been trying ems and rems and most of the times things got messy on mobile devices, especialy when using jQuery elements. Setting the sizes back to px solved these things.\n\nSidenote: my websites are simple and clean and I don\'t use a lot of different font-sizes. But after using ems, rems and percentages and who knows what, I got a little bit anoyed by calculating line-heights \'n stuff. Because really, I prefer clean measurements, not a line-height of 24,3px for example. (Don\'t even get me started about letter-spacing, what a mess...)\n\nI don\'t see the logic to use the 10px rem trick, because I ended up writing everything in rems instead of px. Why not use px in the first place? (margin-left: 2.5 rem = margin-left: 25px)\n\nThe best part is that you don\'t have to worry about older browsers and the nested em \'bug\'. I see a lot of people using px as a fallback as well, that kinda tells me something...\n\nFor everyone out there who thinks that there is a certain rule about this; there isn\'t. You decide whatever works best for you.',0,'1','','',0,0),
