	(3256,54,'Larry','lutzle@swbell.net','','38.100.76.235','2010-06-02 15:51:45','2010-06-02 20:51:45','There are many ways to do a multi-column/equal height layout without tables, one of which is described in http://matthewjamestaylor.com/blog/equal-height-columns-cross-browser-css-no-hacks.\n\nHowever, you didn\'t mention the single most important reason to use css for multi-column layouts which is accessibility and SEO. By using floated columns, you can ensure that the content of your page comes before all the extranous markup for a navigation column, a column of lesser importance, etc.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3257,54,'TI Facil','Figueiras@gmail.com','http://tifacil.blog.com','195.168.109.60','2010-06-07 13:16:00','2010-06-07 18:16:00','Hi, thanks for the post? Is your site a free theme or paid? I am intrigued by your site. Is it possible to include this post on one of my blogs?, i will of course link to this blog. Many Thanks',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3258,74,'Thanh Tri','thanhtribkit@gmail.com','http://it4u.vn','115.78.0.69','2009-11-11 05:16:37','2009-11-11 09:16:37','Sorry, but I think if you specify margin and padding for li and ul element, it won\'t effect correctly because li is inline element, usually i set display:block and use floating instead display:inline for setting margin and padding correctly.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3259,74,'Kyle','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','204.111.87.244','2009-11-11 09:59:13','2009-11-11 13:59:13','Tanh, you could definitely use \"display: block; float: left;\" for the unordered list items as well -- this is something I have used in the past, and it\'s a totally viable option (if not a better one).',0,'1','','',0,0),
