	(3580,178,'Su','suthida.chairatananuwat@citi.com','','192.193.221.140','2011-12-15 18:59:28','2011-12-15 23:59:28','Excellent information!  Very clear, concise explanation on an important topic that pertains to all web site development involving print considerations.  Your instructions successfully accomplished the goal of helping me to understand how this process can be done.  Appreciate you taking the time to share your knowledge with others.  Thank you so much!',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3581,201,'ron','spam@1eyebrow.com','http://1eyebrow.com','199.243.157.178','2009-05-17 13:04:02','2009-05-17 18:04:02','Hey, thanks for the great article. Is there anyway easy way to center the  tags while using the absolute value? 50% left or right starts from the edge of the item so it is not accurate if people are viewing at different sizes.\n\nThanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3582,201,'Kyle','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','64.203.175.98','2009-05-21 10:17:44','2009-05-21 15:17:44','Hi, Ron.  Yes!  You can do that with a little CSS trick where you position the element to 50% left, and then you take away half of that element\'s width in order to center it (via a negative left margin).  It goes something like this:\n\n.centeredElement { width: 400px; position: absolute; top: 50px; left: 50%; margin-left: -200px; }\n\nAs you can see, the \"centeredElement\" has a width of 400 pixels, and then we used the left margin to move the element 200 pixels to the left, thus centering the absolutely positioned element at 50% of it\'s parent.',0,'1','','',3581,0),
	(3583,201,'cris','fakeemailforstupidstuff@yahoo.com','','98.119.141.181','2009-10-04 04:58:50','2009-10-04 08:58:50','Interesting stuff, I\'ve read several posts and it has cleared up alot of confusion about CSS.\n\nTy, cris',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3584,201,'fred','ehpastel@hotmail.com','','117.47.215.3','2010-02-06 13:34:47','2010-02-06 18:34:47','Hi there,\n\nyou said \"The easiest way to avoid this is to set the parent element’s height to a fixed value\" and then you set a height of 3em to the container div, which actually seems to be a very easy way :) but real world often isn\'t that simple. Do you know how to expand the container div height dynamically?\n\nThanks,\nFred',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3585,201,'Kyle','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','204.111.110.237','2010-02-06 15:52:58','2010-02-06 20:52:58','Fred, I would only recommend using absolute positioning for elements of your site design that are fixed in size (header images, menus, navigation, etc.).  If you\'re applying an absolute position to an element that has dynamic content, your best bet is probably to use jQuery or other client script to position and resize your content.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3586,201,'Rahul Bansal','rahul286@gmail.com','http://rtcamp.com','121.246.216.43','2010-12-09 06:25:20','2010-12-09 10:25:20','<strong>@Kyle</strong>\njQuery is a nice suggestion but by any chance, can we do this in CSS alone?\nIts fin if CSS-only hack doesn\'t work in IE6. Just curious...',0,'1','','',0,0),
