	(3645,348,'Shadow','marcinkopec83@gmail.com','','92.20.76.65','2011-12-13 11:42:11','2011-12-13 16:42:11','Is it possible to send a query and get data from database? \ni.e. \nTab One\n(mysql_query = \"\nSELECT\nid_food,\nname\nFROM `food`\nORDER BY id_food\nLIMIT $x, $y\")\n\ntab_second\nmysql_query(\"\nSELECT\nid_food,\nname\nFROM `food`\nWHERE`veg`=1\nORDER BY id_food\nLIMIT $x, $y\n\");\nand so on...\n\nAny examples?\nthx',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3646,348,'Solo','sameera.nishshanka@gmail.com','http://www.netpuppy.blogspot.com','203.153.223.90','2012-03-01 13:46:40','2012-03-01 18:46:40','Working awesome..thanks a lot :)',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3647,348,'Peter','peter@edenweb.ie','http://www.edenweb.ie','109.77.223.183','2012-04-16 07:57:21','2012-04-16 11:57:21','Hi Kyle\nThanks for the great tutorial. \nI wanted to link directly to a specific tab from another page and managed to get it working by using the following code which I reused from another tab tutorial. Might need to be tidied up but could be of interest to some readers here.\n\n[code]\n\n	$(document).ready(function(){\n		$(\".ui-tabs\").tabs()\n		$(\'.ui-tabs\').tabs(); // make jquery tabs\n		$(\".ui-tabs\").tabs(\"select\", window.location.hash);\n		\n	});\n\n[/code]',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3648,348,'mohammed','moh.nasrallah@gmail.com','','77.238.220.250','2012-11-20 19:57:56','2012-11-21 00:57:56','Thanks :)',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3649,358,'Spenser','spenser.baldwin@gmail.com','http://www.spenserbaldwin.com','74.36.124.38','2009-11-19 20:12:10','2009-11-20 00:12:10','When \'text-indent\' is used, doesn\'t this defeat the purpose of providing for users that have images turned off? Perhaps I missed something in the explanation.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3650,358,'Kyle','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','204.111.122.8','2009-11-20 01:36:56','2009-11-20 05:36:56','Spenser, that\'s a great question! I haven\'t actually seen a lot of users who view websites with images disabled; I think that\'s a very small demographic, if at all. Really, when I say \"for users with images disabled,\" I\'m actually talking about software; either search engines or for visually impaired readers, where websites are actually described to them via text-to-speech software. In our example, the software can easily interpret a simple text link. As you can imagine, images are much harder for software to understand, and are at a disadvantage as a result.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3651,358,'inkubator','inkubator2001@mail.ru','http://goge.info','66.96.128.64','2010-01-19 04:00:52','2010-01-19 09:00:52','Бутафория получается',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3652,358,'Grant','billbantam@yahoo.com','','194.106.52.120','2012-10-03 08:21:38','2012-10-03 12:21:38','3 years later... \n\nI sometimes turn off foreground images.  And my daily surfing habits involve using a browser with no background images turned on.\n\nI do this to make sites more legible.  When you get fed up of zooming in on web pages and cutting and pasting text just to read it - you have a change of tact.  I customised my browser.\n\nYour solution should appease text readers.  But I\'m left with a black hole in the page.  \n\nWhile you could argue that I\'m in the minority, the lunatic \'special needs\' fringe, I actually think that the attitude of appeasing the masses over the few is the wrong attitude.  Read your opening paragraph.',0,'1','','',3650,0),
	(3653,400,'Kyle','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','64.203.175.98','2010-01-12 10:46:12','2010-01-12 15:46:12','You may have noticed that comments now have profile images. If you want to add your own image, just sign up for an account at <a href=\"http://www.gravatar.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">gravatar.com</a>.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3654,422,'Karate Corners: XHTML/CSS Rounded Corners / Kyle Schaeffer&#039;s Web Design Blog','','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com/tutorials/karate-corners-easy-rounded-corners-xhtml-no-script/','70.32.68.173','2010-01-31 00:05:21','2010-01-31 05:05:21','[...] Update: Read my subsequent post for a more advanced example of this technique! Update: Read a even more advanced version of this technique in an even newer tutorial! Update: Find out how to automatically generate the HTML and CSS for this technique using jQuery. [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),
	(3655,422,'maruthi','maruthi9999@lycos.com','','65.242.96.10','2010-02-19 15:17:00','2010-02-19 20:17:00','Hi!\nDo you have the example/demo of this\n\nThanks\nMaruthi',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3656,422,'Lou','jacobsen.lone@gmail.com','','90.184.7.215','2010-02-24 05:23:53','2010-02-24 10:23:53','Hi - thanks for a good tutorial. Would it be possible to use this jquery to add rounded corners to images?\nI have been looking for at way to do that, but have not found at good one yet......\nregards, Lou',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3657,422,'Kyle Schaeffer','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','204.111.94.245','2010-02-24 09:13:06','2010-02-24 14:13:06','Hi, Lou.  Yes, you could certainly apply this to an image as well -- you\'ll just have to surround the image with a <code>&lt;div class=&quot;corners&quot; /&gt;</code>, and the corners will be applied directly on top of your image.  You might have to set the height/width of the <code>&lt;div/&gt;</code> to ensure that the corners aren\'t drawn on the far-side of the page, but it should definitely work.  Good luck!',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3658,422,'matt','mrmattholt@gmail.com','','207.156.9.1','2010-04-15 14:03:30','2010-04-15 19:03:30','This just made my day. Thanks',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3659,422,'jaya','chitraamani@yahoo.com','','122.164.173.7','2010-05-07 08:15:02','2010-05-07 13:15:02','The corner radius issue of IE gonna solve.\n\nhttp://kbala.com/ie-9-supports-corner-radius/',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3660,422,'Kyle Schaeffer','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','64.203.175.98','2010-05-07 08:34:28','2010-05-07 13:34:28','Can I just say \"It\'s about damned time!\"',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3661,422,'Si','dalboz@gmail.com','http://frostnova.net','59.154.179.18','2010-08-26 02:48:48','2010-08-26 06:48:48','Why would this not be working in IE6? I love it but 90% of our clients still use IE6.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3662,422,'Kyle','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','68.229.126.69','2010-08-27 21:33:51','2010-08-28 01:33:51','Hi, Si.  You should probably disable rounded corners for IE6 users -- they should be used to seeing the \"dumbed down\" version of websites, so rounded corners are most likely the last thing they would expect. You can do this by attaching an IE6-only CSS style sheet and hiding the corners there, or you could simply change the IE-specific comment line to be <strong>[if gt IE 6]</strong>.\n\nAlternatively, you might be able to do some CSS hacks like <strong>zoom:1</strong> on all the corner boxes to try and clean it up on IE6 browsers. This is something I generally avoid getting into, but it\'s one avenue of development you could pursue if you\'re interested.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3663,488,'Rich','rich.bradshaw@gmail.com','http://bradshawenterprises.com','94.169.192.9','2010-03-15 18:04:23','2010-03-15 23:04:23','No demo?',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3664,488,'Kyle','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','204.111.178.214','2010-03-15 21:39:24','2010-03-16 02:39:24','Rich, thanks for the suggestion!  I\'ve added a demo to the tutorial (above).',0,'1','','',0,0),
