	(3823,565,'Markyys','jesusthefrog@gmail.com','http://code.google.com/p/jquery-gopher-prompt/','140.32.7.88','2012-10-10 10:59:54','2012-10-10 14:59:54','I have adapted your code example into a jQuery plugin. Check it out if you\'re interested.\nUnlike Florian\'s, it follows the objectives laid out in the description of intended functionality.\n\nThanks for this post; it was exactly what I needed.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3824,612,'Grant','gzabrisk@gmail.com','','128.187.97.2','2010-08-11 11:58:18','2010-08-11 15:58:18','Thank you for this article. I help solidify some things I\'ve been thinking and taught me some new things. I have one question. I really like the idea of setting the base font size to 62.5%, which you said is best for users. I\'m just curious why that is. I can see how easy it would make things for me (with 12px being equal to 1.2em, 14px = 1.4em etc...) but how does it help users. It would be great to hear back from about this. Thanks!',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3825,612,'Kyle','schaeffer.kyle@gmail.com','http://www.kyleschaeffer.com','68.229.126.69','2010-08-11 14:18:02','2010-08-11 18:18:02','Hi, Grant -- that\'s a great question. As I discussed in a <a href=\"http://www.kyleschaeffer.com/best-practices/css-font-size-em-vs-px-vs-pt-vs/\" rel=\"nofollow\">previous post</a>, the main reason for using percent (%) on the body tag is to preserve font scalability (so users can enlarge the fonts on your site if necessary).  Some designers may choose to use pixels (px) and encourage users to utilize the \"zoom\" feature in many modern browsers (which is acceptable), but I choose to use percent instead.\n\nPersonally, I feel that as long as the \"text size\" feature is available in browsers, you can count on some users modifying it to make their browsing experience easier.  It\'s easy for you and me to zoom in and out on a website because we are designers...the internet is our domain.  For your average user, however, these browser features might not be as easy -- if they see a \"font size\" setting, they\'re going to click on it.  They might not even know a \"zoom\" feature is available.  As long as that\'s the case, I will continue to use percent for the base font size.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3826,612,'Grant','gzabrisk@gmail.com','','128.187.97.2','2010-08-13 12:28:32','2010-08-13 16:28:32','Kyle - I think that makes perfect sense. Thank you for the explanation. I\'ll be sticking around your site to learn more!',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3827,612,'Kamal','kamal@techtoll.in','http:www.techtoll.in','123.238.178.161','2012-11-06 13:10:59','2012-11-06 18:10:59','Thank you for the article. After reading the caution of Black and white I too changed the color of my site (www.techtoll.in) to somewhat less contrasting.  \n\nGreat article!',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3828,612,'Dioni','','','86.63.2.10','2013-03-13 08:49:34','2013-03-13 12:49:34','I do background and color chagnes a lot, using something likea:active,a:hover,a:focus{background:yellow; color:red;}as a stylesheet line for a whole site. (Obviously, the color choices are up to you, and I see mine got eaten a bit by Y!A because of line length.)Notice a couple things here: the first is that I use a:focus along with the other cases. Sometimes, it\'s useful to tab through the links on a page, and this causes the same color chagnes to highlight a link when it becomes the focus point.The next thing to notice is that I don\'t mess with changing size, weight, or family of the font. Moreover, I specifically disrecommend doing so, because it can change the size of the link on the page and force the whole page to be respaced. There\'s very little that\'s more annoying than having elements surrounding the link move around just because you hover on the link. It pulls the user\'s attention away from the element both you and they want to have their full attention: the link itself.The only thing in Web design that\'s even better than knowing how to do lots of things, is knowing which of them not to do.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3829,638,'Maltenrazer','maltenrazer@gmail.com','','92.25.20.89','2010-11-05 20:30:28','2010-11-06 00:30:28','Simple, Elegant, Powerful!\n\nI love your approach and this site.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3830,638,'Enon','mail@enonavital.com','http://enonavital.com/','173.63.175.119','2010-11-23 02:33:12','2010-11-23 06:33:12','Logo as an h1? I think not...\n\nRead up on a convincing resolution to the age-old debate here: http://csswizardry.com/2010/10/your-logo-is-an-image-not-a-h1/',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(3831,638,'Kyle','kylersc@gmail.com','','68.229.126.69','2010-11-23 10:52:41','2010-11-23 14:52:41','Enon, there is certainly some dissension when it comes to best practices in logo markup, and it\'s great that you bring up the opposing view for the sake of debate.  Most people argue the content vs. style when it comes to logo, which is an important argument to consider.\n\nThe fact of the matter is that the &lt;h1&gt; tag provides an excellent place for search keywords. Whether you think it\'s content or style, the simple pragmatics of keyword placement often tips the scales in this debate.  You can get a huge boost in search ranking simply by placing intelligent, natural, and targeted keywords in &lt;h1&gt; tags across every page of your site.  Regardless of which side of this debate you fall on, that\'s a very compelling advantage of the &lt;h1&gt; approach.\n\nIf you\'re interested in learning more about search optimization, I highly recommend Aarron Walter\'s <a href=\"http://buildingfindablewebsites.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Building Findable Websites</a>.  In his book, he has an entire chapter devoted to \"How to Use Heading Tags,\" where he discusses the importance of using &lt;h1&gt; for your organization/site name.\n\nBest of luck!\nKyle',0,'1','','',0,1),
