	(4058,898,'Container overflow issue','','http://bizzteams.com/forum/html-css/39034-container-overflow-issue.html#post382147','109.206.172.186','2012-07-30 06:40:28','2012-07-30 10:40:28','[...] &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://lorempixel.com/300/300/abstract/10&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;300&quot; height=&quot;300&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;  so when there&#039;s not enough width, first the become only one above the other instead of in pairs, then th ewhole div drops down.  You would do better to make everything, including images, margins, padding etc. % widths. Media queries can do this by making images max-width: 100%; see Responsive Layouts Using CSS Media Queries | Kyle Schaeffer - Web Design and SharePoint Branding [...]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),
