	(4312,1272,'Roy Graphenreed','roy@eprock.com','http://www.eprock.com','8.29.106.10','2013-02-07 08:24:52','2013-02-07 13:24:52','Kyle great article, I will be sure reference the books.  I really like your blog it is really user friendly.\n\nRegards,',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(4313,1272,'Steve O\'Donnell','stephen.odonnell@duke.edu','','152.16.53.21','2013-02-07 12:06:47','2013-02-07 17:06:47','I\'m a communications guy, not a web guy. Consequently, I often find myself in meetings where a web design person tries to explain how the site works, where the user is supposed to go, why the interface is intuitive, even though I\'ve asked a series of questions that indicates it really isn\'t. \"When\'s the last time,\" I usually ask, \"did you go on a website where the first thing you saw was a form that said \'Please give us your name, street address and zip code so that we can send you a copy of the user manual for our site?\'\" The point is, if you need a user manual (or any other kind of explanation), it isn\'t a good site.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(4314,1272,'John','yafzy3j@dispostable.com','','130.65.240.137','2013-03-23 17:48:09','2013-03-23 21:48:09','If Henry Ford had this mentality, he would have made a faster horse—rather than building a car.\n\n\"If I had asked people what they wanted, they would have said faster horses.\"\n\nI wouldn\'t argue with my doctor about which kind of medicine I should take. He\'s the doctor, he should know.\n\nI suppose \"the customer is always right\" is a saying that only applies in certain professions. It\'s definitely not universally relavent.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(4315,1324,'Matthew','matthewkoon@zoomasoft.com','http://www.zoomasoft.com','208.70.19.198','2013-08-08 12:40:00','2013-08-08 16:40:00','Hey Kyle,\n\nI made some minor adjustments to the positioning and added a transparent background so you could see the ribbon and scrollbar. Also, if you\'re using jquery-ui in your solution you could call \"draggable\" on that element in case you wanted to drag it out of the way of something.\n\n\n#MSOTlPn_MainTD {\n  display: block;\n  position: fixed;\n  top: 73px;\n  right: 10px;\n  z-index: 1000;\n  height: 100% !important;\n  width: auto !important;\n  overflow-y: auto;\n  background: transparent;\n}\n',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(4316,1324,'Kyle','kylersc@gmail.com','','204.111.89.195','2013-08-08 12:42:43','2013-08-08 16:42:43','Nice!  Thanks, Matt!',0,'1','','',4315,1),
	(4317,1336,'Keith Tuomi','ktuomi@itgroove.net','http://yalla.itgroove.net','206.47.8.120','2013-08-06 13:53:23','2013-08-06 17:53:23','Thanks for Sharing, Kyle. Would love to check out the source files, so please do make available if the opportunity presents itself.\n\nAm interested to know if you are using a particular CSS minimization ruleset/tool, or are just organizing things by hand?',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(4318,1336,'Jakes','jakes.coetzee@gmail.com','','194.24.1.6','2013-08-13 10:07:03','2013-08-13 14:07:03','Stumled across your blog today, loved this article as well as others, thanks for sharing.\n\nI (like Keith) would like to know if you have a minimization ruleset or tool. Given the numbers doing it by hand must take ages...',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(4319,1336,'Kyle','kylersc@gmail.com','','64.203.175.98','2013-08-13 10:45:33','2013-08-13 14:45:33','Thanks! Yes, I use YUI Compressor (an online one can be found at http://refresh-sf.com/yui/). The only catch in SharePoint is that any rich text editor CSS classes (.ms-rte-) MUST end with a semi-colon.  YUI Compressor will remove these semi-colons, so you need to add them back in to prevent errors.',0,'1','','',4318,1),
	(4320,1336,'Kyle','kylersc@gmail.com','','204.111.120.150','2013-08-13 21:27:50','2013-08-14 01:27:50','Thanks, Keith.  You can get all 16 minified versions of SharePoint 2013 CSS files here:  https://spblueprint.codeplex.com/',0,'1','','',4317,1),
