	(4332,1423,'Richard Innis','rich@mediabrite.com','','132.200.32.34','2013-09-27 09:26:38','2013-09-27 13:26:38','Great article. I\'m certainly guilty of letting the client convince me that pointless stock photography was a requirement. I\'ve also had clients that agreed to foot the bill for high-quality focused (=$$$) rights managed photography and ones that agreed to have us do a shoot and use that imagery over and over again throughout various projects. The times an additional investment was made for strong content, the client (and I) was always pleased with the results.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(4333,1452,'Steve Whetstone','stevedashwhetstone@gmail.com','http://stevewhetstone.com','50.0.92.162','2014-03-10 00:47:53','2014-03-10 04:47:53','Any thoughts on the maintenance lifecycle costs of a REST based design?  I recently worked with a REST based sharepoint design that either wasn\'t passed off well or maybe I didn\'t know the tool I needed to revise and edit it.  I found about a hundred lines of minified Javascript that looked like what I see in your video and the solution was to throw it out and start over.  It seems like there must be some third party tool or something to help because editing that kind of code as a consultant was cost prohibitive.    In my situation the problem seemed to magnifyied by trying to force REST technology to to create old school table layouts and hacks that would have been pretty convoluted HTML even without REST so a lot of the problem would go away with a responsive framework and semantic HTML, but the fundamental problem of editing a REST design for anything more than a minor change on anything more than a simple page eluded me.',0,'1','','',0,0),
	(4334,1452,'Kyle','kyle@oldrivercreative.com','','204.111.99.59','2014-03-10 09:41:33','2014-03-10 13:41:33','Hi, Steve.  A hundred lines of minified JavaScript seems excessive. I\'ve written some very simple and very powerful solutions using REST in only a few lines of code.  That\'s kind of the point.  It may be that the particular solution you\'re working with was not built in an efficient manner. REST is definitely not for everyone. It\'s value really depends on the team you\'re working with.  This technology is in a gray area between front-end development (HTML, CSS, JavaScript, AJAX, etc.) and back-end development (C#, SQL, CAML, etc.).  Almost every \"developer\" focuses on server-side technology, and almost every \"designer\" focuses on the front-end, which makes this a very difficult task to assign.  For this to work well, you need someone who understands both sides, and that can be difficult to find.',0,'1','','',4333,1),
	(4335,1491,'Peter Cuttriss','petecuttriss@hotmail.com','','210.55.180.235','2014-04-30 18:16:25','2014-04-30 22:16:25','Very cool Kyle, thanks for posting.',0,'1','','',0,0),
